RNN vs LSTM
-----------

| Feature                                         | RNN | LSTM            |
| ----------------------------------------------- | --- | --------------- |
| Remembers short sequences                       | ✅   | ✅               |
| Remembers long sequences                        | ❌   | ✅               |
| Suffers from vanishing gradient                 | ✅   | Greatly reduced |
| Memory cell                                     | ❌   | ✅               |
| Forget Gate                                     | ❌   | ✅               |
| Input Gate                                      | ❌   | ✅               |
| Output Gate                                     | ❌   | ✅               |
| Suitable for long text, speech, and translation | ❌   | ✅               |


=======

Simple Analogy

Imagine you are reading a long novel.

RNN is like someone who remembers only the last few pages. By the end, they may forget an important clue from the first chapter.
LSTM is like someone who keeps a notebook. Whenever an important clue appears, they write it down and keep it until it becomes useful later.
This helps them answer questions correctly even after reading many chapters.


==========

In one sentence: RNN struggles with long-term dependencies because important information fades during training (vanishing gradients), 
while LSTM uses a memory cell and gates to selectively store, retain, and retrieve important information over long sequences.

